recordings.rmk:
A single individual emerged from the grass and perched in a 4m tall Box Elder tree about at about 2/3 the tree's height and issued the squeaky calls before then flying north when harassed by a Northern Cardinal. This mp3 has been excerpted from the same .wav file that contains XC288984.

# Habitat #
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

# Editing #
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 1 khz, order 3.

# Equipment #
Fostex FR-2 digital field recorder with Telinga Pro 22" parabolic reflector

recordings.loc: Wolf Road Prairie (near  Chicago), Cook County, Illinois
recordings.rmk:
early spring dawn chorus in a prairie habitat that has a small wetland area and is part of a greenway system that includes oak savanna/prairie and mixed deciduous forest This prairie is directly surrounded by suburban development and is adjacent to a busy street.

There are many species in this short recording and identities of any of them would be appreciated.  The loudest song is, I think, an American Goldfinch, and that is where you all come in.  

Birds have regional dialects and the online databases have birds from all over the world, which have different dialects than the birds I hear around here.  This bird sounds a bit like a goldfinch, yet then again it doesn't.  

Thanks for your help.
